onsequently, we identify 4 layers as the optimal configuration. This choice represents the most favorable trade-off, securing the vast majority of the performance gain while minimizing the additional parameter budget, thereby ensuring high inference efficiency. 8 Taxonomy of Full-Duplex Scenarios To intuitively demonstrate the interaction quality of Lychee-FD, we move beyond isolated examples and analyze user inte", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-818061cd75ad5ee7", "type": "tool_result", "content": "# Moshi: a speech-text foundation model for real-time dialogue\narXiv: 2410.00037\nAuthors: Alexandre Défossez, Laurent Mazaré, Manu Orsini, Amélie Royer, Patrick Pérez, Hervé Jégou, Edouard Grave, Neil Zeghidour\nYear: 2024 | Venue: \nTopic: dialogue_system\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We present Helium, a 7B-parameter text LLM pre-trained on 2.1T tokens of filtered public English data.\n  2. We train Mimi, a neural audio codec that distills semantic information into the first level of acoustic tokens using a split residual vector quantizer.\n  3. We propose a new hierarchical, streaming architecture for audio language modeling that extends the RQ-Transformer with per-codebook parameters and acoustic delays to jointly generate semantic and acoustic tokens.\n  4. We introduce a multi-stream audio language model architecture that explicitly processes the input and output audio streams in parallel to handle full-duplex dialogues with arbitrary conversational dynamics.\n  5. We introduce Inner Monologue, a training and inference method that predicts time-aligned text tokens as a prefix to audio tokens to significantly improve the linguistic quality of generated speech while remaining compatible with streaming inference.\n  6. We demonstrate that adjusting the delay between text and audio tokens within the Inner Monologue framework allows a single model to function as both a streaming ASR and a streaming TTS system.\n\nTags: LALM, 压缩, TTS, LALM/对话型, LALM/音频标记-融合, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-混合, TTS/功能-流式", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "8f247e4b-ee9e-488a-9f6a-0780fd6e7b50", "uuid": "ae453d2a-f66e-413b-abf6-ad100dff6e57", "timestamp": "2026-07-11T17:28:20.505Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "# Moshi: a speech-text foundation model for real-time dialogue\narXiv: 2410.00037\nAuthors: Alexandre Défossez, Laurent Mazaré, Manu Orsini, Amélie Royer, Patrick Pérez, Hervé Jégou, Edouard Grave, Neil Zeghidour\nYear: 2024 | Venue: \nTopic: dialogue_system\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We present Helium, a 7B-parameter text LLM pre-trained on 2.1T tokens of filtered public English data.\n  2. We train Mimi, a neural audio codec that distills semantic information into the first level of acoustic tokens using a split residual vector quantizer.\n  3. We propose a new hierarchical, streaming architecture for audio language modeling that extends the RQ-Transformer with per-codebook parameters and acoustic delays to jointly generate semantic and acoustic tokens.\n  4. We introduce a multi-stream audio language model architecture that explicitly processes the input and output audio streams in parallel to handle full-duplex dialogues with arbitrary conversational dynamics.\n  5. We introduce Inner Monologue, a training and inference method that predicts time-aligned text tokens as a prefix to audio tokens to significantly improve the linguistic quality of generated speech while remaining compatible with streaming inference.\n  6. We demonstrate that adjusting the delay between text and audio tokens within the Inner Monologue framework allows a single model to function as both a streaming ASR and a streaming TTS system.\n\nTags: LALM, 压缩, TTS, LALM/对话型, LALM/音频标记-融合, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-混合, TTS/功能-流式", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
